Author::::derekcolman
DateTime::::2016-03-06T22:20:00Z
The basic physics does not support the catastrophic warming scenario. So far we are on course for a 1° C warming for a doubling of CO2. Starting with the pre-industrial level of 280 ppm of atmospheric CO2, it has to reach 560 ppm to add 1°, 1120 ppm to add 2°, 2240 ppm to reach 3°, and so on. At the current rate of increase it would take almost a millenium to reach 3°, and there is no reason to believe that 3° would be especially dangerous. We are unlikely to be burning fossil fuels for another millenium anyway, so that is hardly likely to happen. None of that takes into account that there will be a saturation point where additional CO2 ceases to have any effect. This is because IR at the frequencies that react with CO2 is a finite supply. Some scientists think we have already reached that saturation point and that explains the 18 plus years decelleration in rising temperature. So far the predicted 2° positive feedback from water vapour has not shown its face, and therefore probably does not existThe satellite record shows the expected rise in temperature from a powerful El Nino. As with previous El Ninos, the following La Nina is likely to pull the temperature down again. It remains to be seen if the hiatus will then continue or whether global warming will resume. BTW, I am using the conventional physics here, which I do not subscribe to as it ignores other factors like the overlap between water vapour and CO2 absorption, and changes in the Sun's magnetic field, and gravitational pull from the major planets.



