Author::::derekcolman
DateTime::::2016-03-06T13:04:07Z
Of course I don't know what tariffs you are on, but I doubt that your electricity is five times as much as gas. In my case I am paying exactly three times as much per kWh equivalent for electricity as for gas. As there is little difference in efficiency between the two with a modern boiler, my current £660 a year for gas would become £1,980 if I swapped to electric heating. As I am only just clear of fuel poverty at present, that would mean I could no longer afford to heat my home. However, I believe that's only half the story. With the likelihood that electricity will double in price in real terms as more renewable energy comes on stream, and the plan to ban gas for home heating in 2030, I think that householders will be faced with paying 6 times as much in real terms for their home heating. That would mean maybe a third to a half of the population would no longer have home heating because they simply will not be able to afford it. However it is likely that people will do just what we did in the winter of 1947, when the snow was so deep that coal deliveries stopped. Where I lived all the able bodied men on the estate assembled in the woods with a variety of saws and cut up the trees for fuel. Luckily they were trees that had been felled by a gale, but if the powers that be take away the ablity to heat our homes, expect wholesale illegal clearing of trees and a black market in wood.



